<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug B</strong> — The riddle and its answer should share the <strong>same</strong> index. Here question 0 is checked against answer 1, so a correct guess is marked wrong.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">questions = [&quot;four legs, cannot walk?&quot;, &quot;cold, melts fast?&quot;]
answers   = [&quot;table&quot;, &quot;ice&quot;]
guess = game.ask(questions[0]).strip()
if guess == answers[1]:
    game.say(&quot;correct&quot;)
else:
    game.say(&quot;wrong&quot;)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> match the answer index to the question index.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug C</strong> — The endings should split by score: 3 = wise, 2 = hero, else = beginner. Right now every score over 0 gives the same ending, because separate <code>if</code>s overwrite each other.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">score = 3
if score &gt;= 1:
    ending = &quot;beginner&quot;
if score &gt;= 2:
    ending = &quot;hero&quot;
if score == 3:
    ending = &quot;wise&quot;
game.say(ending)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> use <code>if</code> / <code>elif</code> / <code>else</code> and check the <strong>highest</strong> score first.</p>
